Author: jaxxxxxxyyyy
Content: I have to agree with Zach here about it. Indonesia should treat smoking as an actual problem since it had been abandoned for too long. Smoking is the leading cause of preventable deaths in Indonesia, as in 2017, it was one of the five major causes of premature deaths. According to the reports from WHO, tobacco kills over 225,700 Indonesians every year. Worse, Indonesia has one of the highest youth smoking rates in the world, with a 2022 survey showed that over 10% of Indonesian children aged 10‚Äì18 years are smokers. I argue this is what benefits Djarum and other smoking companies in certain cases, thus why they will not stop selling cigarettes for the sake of profits. Non-smokers, including children and pregnant women, are exposed to dangerous chemicals through secondhand smoke, and the fact that regulations on tobacco companies are pretty weak in Indonesia doesn't help the case (and warning labels are small and ineffective compared to other countries). I can agree with Zach here that we need regulations on cigarettes and reducing the lower class from using it. Taxation is actually a very common option to reduce the usage for it. @Zach

Author: jaxxxxxxyyyy
Content: Anecdotal evidence, just because some people smoke because of peer pressure or advertising doesn't justify smoking. That's like saying "lots of people drink and drive, so it must be okay." Individual "observation" is not a valid argument, hard data showing smoking‚Äôs health risks still stands no matter how many smokers you find on the streets. Just because something became a "lifestyle" or was once "cool" doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs good or should continue. Where the culture comes from doesn‚Äôt change what smoking actually does to your body. Even today, America regulates smoking more than Indonesia did, which is an irony on why we keep pretending to defend smoking when it should be regulated. Plenty of people create, socialize, and overcome hardship without cigarettes. In this case, cigarettes are unfortunately, surpassing the benefits with more harms without better regulations. This is why I agreed with Zach here.
